  "target_response": {
    "text": "That's the normal physiology of hard intervals, not a red flag. Work intervals are deliberately set past the intensity your oxygen delivery can match, so heavy — even gasping — breathing during the rep is the intended effect; it's the signal you're actually stressing the system you're trying to train. The detail that makes yours benign is the recovery: breathlessness that settles within a minute or two of easing off is effort-matched and self-limiting. The version worth a check-up looks different — breathlessness at rest or with trivial effort, wheezing or a cough that continues long after the session, chest tightness, or breathing that refuses to settle when you stop. None of that matches what you describe, and this morning's numbers are calm too: recovery at 74% with your resting heart rate at its usual level. Keep the intervals in the plan.",
